"Life should be great, rather than long" ~B. R Ambedkar

Ambedkar Jayanti is celebrated on 14th April every year to commemorate the birthday of B.R. Ambedkar. Popularly known as Babasaheb, Ambedkar became one of the first Dalit (untouchables) to obtain a college education in India. He was an Indian jurist, political leader, philosopher, anthropologist, historian, orator, economist, teacher, editor, prolific writer, revolutionary and a revivalist for Buddhism in India. He became the 1st Law Minister of India and also the Chairman of the Constitution Drafting Committee. For his contributions, he was awarded with 'Bharat Ratna'. On Ambedkar Jayanti, various Dalit organizations carry out huge processions. Dalit Melas are held in various parts of the country. 

We here at ISTE NIT Durgapur , remembering the honour and glory of such a prudent and upright man, would like to wish everyone from the inner chords of our heart ,a very happy and sincere Ambedkar jayanti.

Ramadan or Ramazan, the most venerated month of the Hijri calendar, whose onset is celebrated by greeting each other “Ramadan Kareem “and “Ramadan Mubarak” which means “a blessed and generous month to you”. “Ramadan Kareem” marks the beginning of a month of benediction and forgiveness. Ramazan is a month for the ones who have extreme devotion for the almighty. Once Ramazan starts, Muslims should not eat and drink between dawn and sunset for about twenty-nine to thirty days. Fasting symbolizes patience and faith. A month that teaches you the real meaning of humanity and brotherhood. 

We here at ISTE NIT DURGAPUR CHAPTER are extremely rejoiced for such an auspicious journey and wishes everyone “Ramadan Kareem”.

#RamadanKareem

Vaisakhi is a spring harvest festival for Sikhs and Hindus. It is usually celebrated on April 13 or 14 every year. It marks the Sikh new year and commemorates the formation of Khalsa panth of warriors under Guru Gobind Singh in 1699. Vaisakhi is also an ancient festival of Hindus, marking the Solar New Year and also celebrating the spring harvest. Vaisakhi was also the day when colonial British empire officials committed the Jallianwala Bagh massacre on a gathering, an event influential to the Indian movement against colonial rule.

On the festival day, Gurdwaras are decorated and hold kirtans, Sikhs visit and bathe in lakes or rivers before visiting local Gurdwaras, community fairs and nagar kirtan processions are held, and people gather to socialize and share festive foods. For many Hindus, it's an occasion to bathe in sacred rivers such as Ganges, Jhelum and Kaveri, visit temples, meet friends and party over festive foods.

We here at ISTE NIT Durgapur, wish all of you from the inner chords of our heart a very happy and splendid Vaishakhi.

Easter, also called Pascha or Resurrection Sunday,is a Christian festival and holiday commemorating the resurrection of Jesus from the dead, described in the New Testament as having occurred on the third day after his burial following his crucifixion by the Romans at Calvary. It is the culmination of the passion of Jesus, preceded by Lent (or Great Lent), a 40-day period of fasting, prayer, and penance.This day holds a special place in the hearts and minds of millions of Christians as they honour and recognise Jesus Christ's ressurection from the dead and his glorious promises for eternal life with full faith and credence. 

Today, we here at ISTE NIT Durgapur, would like to wish each and everyone of you a very  happy and ecstatic Easter Sunday.

Holi is the time which ushers the welcoming of the spring season and ends the winter blues. To some people, Holi is the festival of love shared by Radha and Krishna, a form of love that needs no specific name. Folklores say that Holika, the aunt of Prahlad and sister of King Hiranyakashipu, was a demoness who was burnt to death with the help of God Vishnu. Thus, the story of Holika Dahan signifies the triumph of good over evil. For most of us, it is an opportunity of fun, frolic, forgiveness and compassion. So come, let's embrace this occasion to wipe bad memories and fill our lives with colours, as we cheerfully chant "Holi Hai" and have some delicacies. 

ISTE NIT Durgapur wishes you all Happy Holi, as we look forward to add some fun and colours to our lives in these bad times.

#holifestival #Holi #festival #happiness

“Revolution is an inalienable right of mankind. Freedom is an imperishable birthright of all”.

-Bhagat Singh.

The day in history, when the world witnessed the divineness of Indian youths, the day that teaches us the true meaning of sanctity of one’s devotion towards its motherland. 23rd march, martyr day of Bhagat Singh, Sukhdev Thapar and Shivaram Rajguru, the day in March 1931, they thought they were hanging the sparks of Indian revolution, what they didn’t realized was “By crushing individuals, they cannot kill ideas”. So today, ISTE NIT DURGAPUR CHAPTER is paying its tribute to the three epitomes of ‘spontaneous overflow of life’. We impulse everyone that no matter how harsh the locus is, we will adhere to it if it escorts us towards freedom and we will keep Bhagat Singh, Sukhdev and Rajguru alive in us.

#shaheeddiwas

World Water Day is observed annually across the globe on March 22 with the purpose of highlighting the importance of water and raising awareness about the water crisis that the world faces.At the present day,water is under extreme threat from a growing population, increasing demands of agriculture and industry, and the worsening impacts of climate change. The value of water is much more than generally thought .It has an enormous and incessant demand for our households, food, culture, health, education, economics and for the integrity of our natural environment. If we overlook its multifaceted importance, we risk mismanaging this finite, irreplaceable resource. Following this year's theme- "VALUING WATER", we here at ISTE NIT Durgapur,would like to wish everyone a very sincere World Water Day and  lay stress on the utmost importance of  preserving such a priceless resource in the future days to come.

In the historical pages of science, 14th March 1879 is engraved in golden letters as it witnessed the birth of a prodigy, one of the most intelligent man that ever walked the earth, Albert Einstein. 
An ordinary kid born in Ulm, Germany who hated school, who hated the education system, nobody knew was a miracle in disguise.  A man with an extraordinary IQ, who gave the world an idea about relativity, an essence about duality of light, proved at every point of his life that "In the middle of difficulty lies the opportunity". 
So ISTE  celebrating this day plea everyone to make a promise to be educated rather than mugging up the facts and numbers, let's experiment rather than simply believing. Let's be a part of what he rightly said "Education is what remains after one has forgotten what one has learned in school".

#BirthAnniversary #SirAlbertEinstein #physics #iste #nitdgp

Maha Shivratri is observed on the Chaturdashi of Krishna Paksha in the month of Phalguna. On this night, the northern hemisphere of the Earth is positioned in such a way that there is a natural upsurge of energy in a human being and a person reaches his spiritual peak. For the ascetics, it is the day he became one with Mount Kailash- being absolutely still. The day is celebrated as the grand marriage of Lord Shiva with Goddess Parvati. Devotees offer Lord Shiva milk, fruits, vegetables, bel patra, and other things. Some keep "Nirjala" fast to observe this day and show their dedication towards the lord.

ISTE NIT Durgapur wishes all of you a blessed and invigorating Maha Shivratri. May Lord Shiva shower you with happiness and prosperity.

"Innovation is seeing what everybody has seen and thinking what nobody has thought." ~Dr. Albert Szent-Gyorgyi
Innovation is an idea that has been transformed into reality, and fosters competitive advantage as it allows to build better products.

Smart India Hackathon (SIH) is a nationwide initiative to provide students with a platform to showcase their skills to solve some of the pressing problems we face in our daily lives, and provide innovative ideas. 

Some of the students have 
shown immense talent and performed exceptionally well in SIH, 2020.
 
The winners are TEAM DRAUNZIT comprising: 
Ankita Mishra (3rd yr.)
Soumyajit Saha (3rd yr.)
Sanniva Bhattacharjee (3rd yr.)
Shivam (3rd yr.)
Subhankar Datta (3rd yr.)
Rajkumar Halder (3rd yr.)

ISTE  NIT Durgapur is proud to have such talented people as members of the society and would like to congratulate them for their endeavour and wish them luck for future.

From ornamenting our lives to turning houses into homes, from guiding the country to protecting us at the border, women contribution towards the development of any nation is unmatched.  Acing the roles of Mother, Sister, Wife, Daughter and Friend, from tolerating all the negativities to binding all the pearls of the society together, women proves to be the most powerful creation of god. 

So this Women’s Day, ISTE urges everyone, let’s embed it in our soul to respect women, to fight for the rights they are being denied and to establish equality in our society. 

Wishing every women out there “YOU ARE BEAUTIFUL, STAY STRONG , HAPPY WOMEN’S DAY”.
